Interface PLJavaBasedLanguage.SRFNext

All Superinterfaces:
AutoCloseable
Enclosing interface:
PLJavaBasedLanguage
public static interface PLJavaBasedLanguage.SRFNext extends AutoCloseable
The result of a firstCall call on an instance of SRFFirst.

The nextResult method will be called repeatedly as long as its return value indicates another row may follow, unless PostgreSQL earlier determines no more rows are needed.

The close method will be called after the last call of nextResult, whether because all rows have been read or because PostgreSQL has read all it needs. It is not called, however, if nextResult has returned Result.SINGLE.

  • Method Details

    • close

      void close()
      Called when PostgreSQL will be making no further calls of nextResult for this result set, which may be before all results have been fetched.

      When a degenerate single-row set is returned (as indicated by nextResult returning Result.SINGLE), this method is not called.

      Specified by:
      close in interface AutoCloseable

    • nextResult

      PLJavaBasedLanguage.SRFNext.Result nextResult(RegProcedure.Call fcinfo) throws SQLException
      Called to return a single result.

      As with non-set-returning routines, this method should store result values into fcinfo.result() or set fcinfo.isNull(true) (which, in this context, produces a row of all nulls). If there is no result to store, the method should return Result.END: no row will be produced, and the result set is considered complete.

      If the method has exactly one row to return, it may store the values and return Result.SINGLE: the result will be considered to be just that one row. None of the rest of the set-returning protocol will be involved, and close() will not be called.

      Otherwise, the method should return Result.MULTIPLE after storing each row, and conclude by returning Result.END from the final call (without storing anything).

      It is a protocol violation to return Result.SINGLE from any but the very first call.

      The arguments in fcinfo.arguments() will not be changing as the rows of a single result are retrieved. Any argument values that will be referred to repeatedly may be worth fetching once in the firstCall method and their Java representations captured in this object, rather than fetching and converting them repeatedly.

      Throws:
      SQLException
